A review of thymic tumours. Tumours of the thymus are uncommon and are generally regarded as being indolent. Whilst this is often true of thymomas thymic adenocarcinoma and thymic neuroendocrine cancer can be aggressive and have a poor prognosis. Understanding the biology of these tumours is important for prognosis and management. The pathological features of these tumours are examined in detail. Imaging modalities for aiding in diagnosis and staging of these tumours are described